The bone house is fascinating even after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairwell resembles the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open with a fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
From the locals, thanks to their organic shapes, he earned a nickname from the House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facades resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all typical of the Art Nouveau Antoni Gaudí.
