Men who have a index finger longer than a ring finger are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Journal.
It could be related to the level of male testosterone hormone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60," said the co-author of the study Ros Eeles, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The breast could thus help to identify who men should undergo prostate cancer tests, especially in combination with genetic risks or other risk factors such as family health burden, added Eeles.
In 1994-2009, she and her colleagues watched more than 1500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men in parallel.
More than half of the study participants had a index finger on the right hand than a ring finger.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were as long.
However, for those who had a index finger longer than a ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent for men up to the age of 60, a decrease of up to 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - shaped in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the various levels of the sex hormones that the child is exposed to in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous studies have shown that testosterone is the one that supports growing prostate cancer.
