Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again appeared with a clear view when she demanded reforming the European Union Conventions so that the rescue of a Member State could be possible, while at the same time allowing private creditors to bear part of their costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European because it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although in a somewhat mitigated form, has been approved, and over the next few months we should be monitoring the Union's reform process, which should allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it is not going to cross.
And it tells us to all that, although it is now necessary to take measures that seem to disagree with them too, from this date on, the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will constitute the birth of a new monetary zone in which countries that infringe the rules will be subject to severe sanctions and may be forced to announce the deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany suggests that we must take a strong path to growth with an increase in savings and investments, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
